label.value: abnormal placental labyrinth villi branching morphogenesis

value.value: any anomaly in the process in which the branches of the fetal placental villi are generated and organized from the trophoblast-derived epithelium

label.value: increased placenta intervillous maternal lacunae size

value.value: increased size of the spaces of the placenta occupied by maternal blood, into which the fetal labyrinth villi project
anomaly of the radius and ulna resulting in some portion of or all the two bones being merged together

any structural anomaly of the multi-nucleated, terminally differentiated syncytial epithelial layer of the placental villi that forms the major nutrient transport surfaces within the labyrinth layer of the rodent placenta

label.value: decreased urine major urinary protein level

value.value: reduced amount in the urine of a family of alpha2-microglobulin-related liver secretory proteins that comprise a major protein component of mouse urine

label.value: increased urine major urinary protein level

value.value: increased amount in the urine of a family of alpha2-microglobulin-related liver secretory proteins that comprise a major protein component of mouse urine

a kidney in which fairly uniform, diffusely and evenly situated foci of scarring of the interstitial tissue of the cortex (and sometimes scarring of glomeruli), and the associated slight degree of bulging of groups of dilated tubules, leads to the development of a minutely bosselated surface; such kidneys are seen in arteriolar nephrosclerosis or chronic glomerulonephritis

increased frequency of urination episodes; urination at short frequent intervals occurs without an increase in daily volume of urinary output and may be caused by reduced bladder capacity or urinary tract infection

definition.value: Clinicians sometimes mistakenly label increased urinary frequency as polyuria (increased urine output); Though rarely used, pollakisuria (or pollakiuria) is the correct term for increased frequency of urination.

value.value: decreased frequency of urination episodes; urination at long intervals occurs without an decrease in daily volume of urinary output
passage of an increased amount of any salt or ester of uric acid (urate) in the urine
any change in the urine amount of any of the chemical substances that have specific regulatory effects on the activity of a certain organ or organs
any change in the urine amount of the hormone that is secreted by the adrenal cortex and regulates sodium conservation and potassium secretion in the distal renal tubule
an increased amount of aldosterone in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of aldosterone in the urine compared to the normal state

any change in the urine amount of the polypeptide hormone secreted by the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland (neurohypophysis) that increases mean arterial pressure by promoting vasoconstriction and reduces excretion of urine by increasing the reabsorption of water by the kidney tubules
an increased amount of antidiuretic hormone in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of antidiuretic hormone in the urine compared to the normal state
any change in the urine amount of the antiestrogenic steroid released by the corpus luteum that stimulates the uterus to prepare for pregnancy
an increased amount of progesterone in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of progesterone in the urine compared to the normal state
any change in the urine amount of the corticosteroid produced in the adrenal cortex that induces glycogen deposition and regulates sodium conservation and potassium secretion
an increased amount of corticosterone in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of corticosterone in the urine compared to the normal state
an irregular and random patchwork of two or more colors in the eye
any change in the urine amount of the steroid hormone secreted by the adrenal cortex, related to corticosterone and involved in regulating water and electrolyte balance
an increased amount of deoxycorticosterone in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of deoxycorticosterone in the urine compared to the normal state
greater than the normal amount of any globulin (or any fragment of a globulin) of low molecular weight in the urine
greater than the normal amount of beta2-microglobulin in the urine; may indicate renal tubule disease, drug-induced renal toxicity, heavy metal-induced renal disease, lymphomas, leukemia, or myeloma

label.value: increased susceptibility to induced choroid neovascularization

value.value: increased rate or amount of new growth of new, abnormal blood vessels that originate in the choroid through a break in the Bruch membrane into the sub-retinal pigment epithelium or subretinal space and may result in visual loss as a result of chemical or mechanical manipulation (e.g. laser-induced trauma)
any change in the amount of insulin in the urine
a greater amount of insulin in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of insulin in the urine compared to the normal state
presence of lipid deposits and/or lipid-laden foam cells in the renal glomerular tufts
any change in the urinary amount of any of a class of mediators with effects of vasodilation, vasoconstriction, and smooth muscle stimulation
a greater amount of any prostaglandin in the urine compared to the normal state
a reduced amount of any prostaglandin in the urine compared to the normal state
underdevelopment or reduced size, usually due to a reduced number of cells, of the apex of the renal pyramid that normally projects into a calyx

deviation from the normal levels, or accumulation of the proteins that act sequentially to allow for the direct killing of microbes, the disposal of immune complexes, and the regulation of other immune processes

distortion of the renal glomerular architecture usually accompanied by increased mesangial cell proliferation and following crowding of the proliferated cells towards the axis of the capillary loops and peripheral recanalization, giving the glomerular tuft a lobular or hypersegmented appearance
visually detectable dilution of pigment present on the foot surface

any structural anomaly of the unpaired vein which in humans arises from the right ascending lumbar vein or the vena cava, enters the thorax through the aortic orifice in the diaphragm, and terminates in the superior vena cava; unlike humans, mice have a single and left-sided azygos vein that develops from the paired embryonic cardinal venous system and drains most of the right and left thoracic walls into the left anterior vena cava
failure of the normal relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter associated with the uncoordinated contractions of the thoracic esophagus, resulting in functional obstruction
increased size of the semicircular fold of endocardium located on the right atrium at the point of attachment of the inferior vena cava

any structural anomaly of the portion of the left ventricular outflow tract delineated by the sinotubular ridge superiorly and the bases of the valve leaflets inferiorly; it comprises the aortic sinuses, the aortic valve leaflets, the commissures, and the interleaflet triangles
any structural anomaly of the point in the ascending aorta where the aortic sinuses end and the aorta becomes a tubular structure
the luminal space of the sinotubular junction is increased in diameter or area
the luminal space of the aorta bulb is increased in volume or area, usually with an increase of contained fluid
absence of the first (topmost, C1) cervical vertebra which supports the globe of the head
anomaly in the ability to catalyze the reaction: triacylglycerol + H2O = diacylglycerol + a carboxylate
